07650nam a22013935i 9780691200071DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2019043761  a97806912000717 a10.1515/97806912000712doi  a(DE-B1597)541408  a(OCoLC)1122715575  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHD5857 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a324.20942231 aPedulla, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking the Cut :bHiring Decisions, Bias, and the Consequences of Nonstandard, Mismatched, and Precarious Employment /cDavid Pedulla. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b21 b/w illus. 5 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1. Hiring in the New Economy -- t2. Nonstandard, Mismatched, and Precarious Work -- t3. Making Meaning of Employment Histories: Signals, Uncertainty, and the Need for a Narrative -- t4. Inclusion and Exclusion in Hiring: The Varied Effects of Nonstandard, Mismatched, and Precarious Employment Histories -- t5. "What Type of a Grown Man Doesn't Have a Full-Time Job?": Gender and Part-Time Work -- t6. "Maybe It's More Natural for Them to Have Been Out of Work for a Little While": Race and Unemployment -- t7. "They Do a Pretty Thorough Background Check": THA Employment and African American Men -- t8. Conclusion -- tMethodological Appendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn in-depth look at how employers today perceive and evaluate job applicants with nonstandard or precarious employment historiesMillions of workers today labor in nontraditional situations involving part-time work, temporary agency employment, and skills underutilization or face the precariousness of long-term unemployment. To date, research has largely focused on how these experiences shape workers' well-being, rather than how hiring agents perceive and treat job applicants who have moved through these positions. Shifting the focus from workers to hiring agents, Making the Cut explores how key gatekeepers-HR managers, recruiters, and talent acquisition specialists-evaluate workers with nonstandard, mismatched, or precarious employment experience. Factoring in the social groups to which workers belong-such as their race and gender-David Pedulla shows how workers get jobs, how the hiring process unfolds, who makes the cut, and who does not.Drawing on a field experiment examining hiring decisions in four occupational groups and in-depth interviews with hiring agents in the United States, Pedulla documents and unpacks three important discoveries. Hiring professionals extract distinct meanings from different types of employment experiences; the effects of nonstandard, mismatched, and precarious employment histories for workers' job outcomes are not all the same; and the race and gender of workers intersect with their employment histories to shape which workers get called back for jobs. Indeed, hiring professionals use group-based stereotypes to weave divergent narratives or "stratified stories" about workers with similar employment experiences. The result is a complex set of inequalities in the labor market.Looking at bias and discrimination, social exclusion in the workplace, and the changing nature of work, Making the Cut probes the hiring process and offers a clearer picture of the underpinnings of getting a job in the new economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEmployee selection. 0aPolitical partieszEurope. 0aPrecarious employment. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aBonnie Oglensky.  aCarroll Seron.  aChris Tilly.  aCynthia Fuchs Epstein.  aEsther Neuwirth.  aFalling from Grace.  aFlawed System/Flawed Self.  aGood Jobs, Bad Jobs.  aJackie Rogers.  aKatherine Newman.  aLauren Rivera.  aLouis Hyman.  aOfer Sharone.  aPedigree.  aPhilip Moss.  aRobert Sauté.  aStories Employers Tell.  aTemp.  aTemps.  aThe Mismatched Worker.  aThe Part-time Paradox.  aaccounting work.  aadministrative work.  abookkeeping work.  aclerical work.  aday laborers.  aeconomic insecurity.  aemployment experiences.  aemployment opportunities.  aexclusive hiring.  afreelance work.  afreelancers.  afull-time work.  ahiring decisions.  ahuman resource management.  ainclusion and exclusion in hiring.  ainclusive hiring.  ajobhunting.  ajobseekers.  alabor and employment relations.  alabor force.  alabor market.  along-term unemployment.  aoccupational culture.  aon-call work.  aon-call workers.  aorganizational studies.  apart-time positions.  aproject management.  asales work.  atemp agencies.  atemporary help.  awork and employment.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069008840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691200071zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691200071423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691200071.jpg  a978-3-11-069008-8  PUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070472-3  